What you do from here — step by step
Hardware setup (do this first, needs Arduino IDE on a laptop)

Open Arduino IDE, open door_mechanism.ino, select board: Tools → Board → Arduino Uno
Plug Arduino into your laptop via USB, select the port: Tools → Port → whichever appears
Click Upload (→ arrow). When it says "Done uploading" you should hear two short beeps from the buzzer. That confirms it worked.
Wire the servo: signal wire → Pin 6, red → 5V, black/brown → GND
Wire the buzzer: (+) → Pin 7, (−) → GND. Must be an active buzzer (has a small circuit board on it), not a passive one
Unplug from laptop, plug Arduino into the PYNQ's USB-A port. Two beeps again = good.

PYNQ setup (do this in Jupyter)

Upload smart_node.py to Jupyter via the file browser
In a new notebook cell, run:

python!pip install pyserial
!jupyter nbextension enable --py widgetsnbextension --sys-prefix
Then restart the kernel: Kernel → Restart

Find your Arduino port — run this in a cell:

pythonimport subprocess
print(subprocess.run(['ls', '/dev/ttyUSB*'], capture_output=True, text=True).stdout)
print(subprocess.run(['ls', '/dev/ttyACM*'], capture_output=True, text=True).stdout)
Copy whatever port appears (e.g. /dev/ttyUSB0)

Open smart_node.py in Jupyter, find ARDUINO_PORT = "/dev/ttyUSB0" near the top and update it if yours is different. Save.
Run the system — in a notebook cell:

pythonexec(open("smart_node.py").read())
You should see the LED cycle through green → cyan → red → white (boot sequence), then "Ready. Waiting for Marcus..."

